tman's Immersion in the "Spanish Element" -- tReading La Patria: Hispanophone Print Culture and the Annexation Question -- tSongs of the Exile: The Laud Poets and Quintero's Pearls -- t5. The Deep Roots of Our America: Two New Worlds, and Their Resistors -- tDiplomatic License: Pombo in New York -- tStaging Gender on the California Borderlands -- tBrave Mundo Nuevo: The Marketing of Transnational Spanish Culture -- tMost Faithful Fidel: Guillermo Prieto's Reconstruction Travelogue -- tCODA The Future's Past: Latino Ghosts in the U.S. Canon -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis polished literary history argues forcefully that Latinos are not newcomers in the United States by documenting a vast network of Spanish-language cultural activity in the nineteenth century. Juxtaposing poems and essays by both powerful and peripheral writers, Kirsten Silva Gruesz proposes a major revision of the nineteenth-century U.S. canon and its historical contexts. Drawing on previously unpublished archival materials and building on an innovative interpretation of poetry's cultural role, Ambassadors of Culture brings together scattered writings from the borderlands of California and the Southwest as well as the cosmopolitan exile centers of New York, New Orleans, and San Francisco. It reads these productions in light of broader patterns of relations between the U.S. and Latin America, moving from the fraternal rhetoric of the Monroe Doctrine through the expansionist crisis of 1848 to the proto-imperialist 1880s. It shows how ''ambassadors of culture'' such as Whitman, Longfellow, and Bryant propagated ideas about Latin America and Latinos through their translations, travel writings, and poems. In addition to these well-known figures and their counterparts in the work of nation-building in Cuba, Mexico, and Central and South America, this book also introduces unremembered women writers and local poets writing in both Spanish and English. In telling the almost forgotten early history of travels and translations between U.S. and Latin American writers, Gruesz shows that Anglo and Latino traditions in the New World were, from the beginning, deeply intertwined and mutually necessary.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / Hispanic American.2bisacsh  aAnzaldúa, Gloria.  aAugier, Angel.  aBennett, Paula B.  aBrodhead, Richard H.  aBryant, William Cullen.  aCatholicism: defense of.  aClay, Henry.  aCortés, Hernán.  aEllert, Elizabeth.  aEspronceda, José de.  aFliegelman, Jay.  aFree Soil Party.  aGustafson, Zadel Barnes.  aGómez de Avellaneda, Gertrudis.  aHispanophilia in United States.  aIturbide, Agustin de.  aJefferson, Thomas.  aKanellos, Nicolás.  aKennedy, James.  aLincoln, Abraham.  aMartell, Helvetia.  aMatthiessen, F. O.  aMignolo, Walter.  aMississippi River.  aNorton, Anne.  aOrientalism.  aPiñeyro, Enrique.  aabolitionism.  aballad form.  acaptivity narratives.  adel Monte, Domingo.  aintellectuals.  apublic sphere.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691221304zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691221304423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691221304.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK